    <p>I'm 64. I built SnapProtein partly because I know what happens when structure disappears — and travel is the best way to make structure disappear fast.</p>

    <p>At home, you've got your routine. The same breakfast, the same lunch you throw together, the same protein sources in the fridge. You don't have to think about it. But the second you're on the road — in a hotel, eating out three times a day, sitting in an airport at 7am — that invisible system collapses. And most men don't even notice until they get home and realize they've been running on 60–70g a day for a week.</p>

    <p>That's the real problem. Not willpower. Not lack of options. <strong>Lack of visibility.</strong></p>

    <p>Here's how to stay on track while traveling — without making it weird, without meal prepping a cooler, and without turning every restaurant into a nutrition negotiation.</p>

