    <h2>Why Travel Kills Protein (And It's Not What You Think)</h2>

    <p>It's not that you can't find protein on the road. It's everywhere — every restaurant has chicken, beef, fish, eggs. The issue is that without your home routine running in the background, you stop <em>seeing</em> the number. You're not intentionally eating less protein. You're just not anchoring meals around it the way you do at home without thinking about it.</p>

    <p>Add in the fact that travel days often come with irregular meal timing, airport food, client dinners where you're not controlling the menu, and late nights — and the protein deficit stacks up quietly. By day 3 of a 5-day trip, most men are significantly behind without realizing it.</p>

    <p>The fix is simple: keep the number visible. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="color: var(--green); font-weight: 600;">What 120g actually looks like</a> doesn't change because you're in a different city. Three meals, 30–40g each, one small snack. That's still the system. You just need to see it while you're doing it.</p>

    <h2>6 Strategies That Actually Work on the Road</h2>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">1</div>
      <h3>Anchor Every Meal With Protein First</h3>
      <p>Before you look at anything else on the menu — sides, appetizers, drinks — identify your protein source. Grilled chicken, steak, salmon, shrimp, eggs. That's your anchor. Everything else fills in around it. This one habit prevents the most common travel mistake: building a meal around carbs and bread and realizing the protein was an afterthought.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">2</div>
      <h3>Know Your Restaurant Defaults</h3>
      <p>Most menus — even average restaurants — have at least two or three options that hit 30g+ without any modification. A 6 oz chicken breast is ~50g. A 6 oz sirloin is ~44g. A salmon fillet is ~34g. You don't need to special-order or ask awkward questions. You just need to know which items on any given menu are your defaults, and order one of them.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">3</div>
      <h3>Work the Hotel Breakfast</h3>
      <p>Hotel breakfasts are underrated protein opportunities. Eggs (3 = ~18g), Greek yogurt if available (~15g), cottage cheese, even sliced deli meat at the buffet. The mistake is filling up on pastries and orange juice and calling it breakfast. Spend 60 seconds identifying the protein first, build the plate around it, and you've started the day with 25–35g before you leave the hotel.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">4</div>
      <h3>Carry Two or Three Travel Snacks</h3>
      <p>You don't need a cooler. Beef jerky (1 oz bag = ~9g), string cheese (1 stick = ~8g), and a protein bar (15–25g depending on brand) fit in a carry-on pocket. These aren't meal replacements — they're gap-fillers for the stretches between meals where your options are terrible and your hunger is real. Knowing you have 15–25g of snack protein in your bag removes most of the desperation ordering that derails travel nutrition.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">5</div>
      <h3>Log It While It's in Front of You</h3>
      <p>This is where most men fall off tracking while traveling. They plan to log after the meal, get distracted, and never do it. The habit that works: open the tracker before you eat. Log what's in front of you while you're deciding how much to eat, not after. It takes 20–30 seconds with a simple tracker and keeps the number visible in real time — which is the whole point.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="strategy-num">6</div>
      <h3>Don't Try to Make Up for Lost Days</h3>
      <p>If you had a low day, don't try to cram an extra 60g into tomorrow. Your body can only use so much protein per meal for muscle protein synthesis — around <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-absorption-per-meal-men-over-40/" style="color: var(--green); font-weight: 600;">30–40g per sitting</a>. Just get back to your normal anchoring approach and let the system work. The goal is a consistent week, not a perfect day.</p>
    </div>

