    <h2>The Tracker That Doesn't Slow You Down</h2>

    <p>The reason most men stop tracking when they travel is that their tracker becomes a burden the moment routine disappears. They can't find the restaurant food in the database. They're not sure what the dish was called. They give up and stop logging entirely.</p>

    <p>SnapProtein works differently by design. You're not searching a database of 8 million foods. You've got your common protein sources already saved. At a restaurant, you pick the closest match — grilled chicken, steak, salmon — log it, and you're done in under 30 seconds. Chad Moeller figured this out on the road before I even had to explain it to him. That's the point. It should work without instructions.</p>

    <p>Travel is actually where simple tracking beats comprehensive tracking. You don't need perfect data. You need to see the number. That's what keeps you from drifting 40–50g below your target without noticing.</p>

